==English==
{{was wotd|2008|September|23}}
[[File:Casamento judeu1.jpg|thumb|Yarmulkes]]
===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|en|yarmalka|yarmalke|yarmelka|yarmelke|yarmulka|yermulke||rhotic variants}}
* {{alter|en|yamaka|yamalka|yamalke|yamelka|yamelke|yamilke|yamuka|yamulka|yamulke||nonrhotic variants}}
===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|yi|יאַרמלקע}}, from {{der|en|pl|jarmułka|t=skullcap}} or a {{der|en|uk|-}} cognate of the same. Possibly from the {{der|en|tr|yağmurluk|t=rainwear}}, though it could also be from {{der|en|ML.|almutia|t=hood, cowl}} (compare {{cog|la|amictus|t=clothed, veiled}}).
===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/ˈjɑːməlkə/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/ˈjɑ(ɹ)mə(l)kə/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-yarmulke.ogg|Audio (US)}}
===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
# A [[skullcap]] worn by [[religious]] [[Jewish]] males (especially during [[prayer]]). {{defdate|from 1903}}
#: {{syn|en|kippah|kappel|skullcap}}
#* {{quote-web|en|date=1991-10-01|title=The New Anti-Semitism: A Geshrei|page=33|work=Village Voice|author=Richard Goldstein|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/01/04/the-new-anti-semitism-a-geshrai/|passage=And I always feel uncomfortable dur­ing the High Holy Days watching people in '''yarmulkes''' rushing through the streets, knowing they’ll be swaying and moaning something ancient and indecipherable, even to me.}}
#* {{quote-web|en|author=Patricia Cohen|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/29/books/29pcoh.html?ex=1179115200|title=The Frozen Dozen|work=New York Times|date=April 29, 2007|passage=But once Dr. Levenson, who works for the Indian Health Service and wears a colorful tapestry '''yarmulke''', has alerted the tiny network, it almost seems as if we have stepped into Yiddishland.}}
